  "original_title": "Sri Lanka appoints committee to facilitate repatriation of refugees from India",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka appoints committee to facilitate repatriation of refugees from India",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka has appointed a committee to facilitate and optimise the repatriation of Sri Lankans who had fled to India as war refugees.",
        "A statement from the president\u2019s media division (PMD) said on Monday September 05 said about 58,000 Sri Lankan refugees are currently residing in Tamil Nadu, India, out of whom only 3,800 are ready to return to Sri Lanka at present.",
        "The committee, headed by Additional Secretary to the President Chandima Wickramasinghe, comprises the Controller General of Immigration and Emigration and senior officials of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Registrar General\u2019s Department and the Ministry of Justice.",
        "The PMD statement said the decision to appoint the committee was reached at a discussion held at the President\u2019s Office on Monday at the request of the Organisation for Eelam Refugees Rehabilitation (OFERR) to bring back the Sri Lankans who had fled to India as refugees due to the war. The discussion was chaired by Secretary to the President Saman Ekanayake.",
        "The Sri Lanka Deputy High Commissioner\u2019s Office in Chennai is coordinating the efforts in this regard, the statement said.",
        "Over 67,000 Sri Lankan refugees have been living in 107 camps scattered across Tamil Nadu, according to a 2019 report by the Refugee Studies Centre in the Oxford Department of International Development, University of Oxford.",
        "Just under 37,000 lived outside the camps at the time of the study.",
        "Sri Lankan Tamil refugees fled the government\u2019s war with the separatist Tamil Tigers at various points of the 26-year conflict.",
        "\u201cAlthough refugees are entitled to residence visas and work permits, prolonged life in the camps does not lead to resilience and empowerment, and these refugees consider themselves in limbo, belonging neither to Sri Lanka nor to India and unable to get on with their lives,\u201d the report said.",
        "\u201cTamil refugees \u2013 especially youth \u2013 wish to be disassociated with the label of \u2018refugee\u2019, which they feel would improve quality of life for them, their families and their communities,\u201d it added. (Colombo/Sep05/2022)"
      ],
